@hapahapahappy Yes, the movie definitely takes a stand on the side of "we need to defeat the oppressive powers that be, make the world a better place, take care of the marginalized...' what have you which btw, isn't a radical position in itself, i thought its admirable to want to make the world a better place? Extremism can arise out of misplaced adventurism (which the movie takes a pretty strong stance on with perfidias character), or more justified reasons (what that might be is a discussion)

Regarding the movie as a whole. i say that its stance  in itself in the end does not contaminate or diminish the larger picture presented throughout the movie about how hilariously incompetent people with this passion can be. It does a great job demonstrating the difference in effectiveness between passion/immaturity vs discipline/rigidity  (leo/perfidia vs del toro/penn), while taking a punt at the sillyness of racial superiority complex thats rearing its ugly head again in the mainstream...And the car chase in the end? No movie fan can deny how its one of the best ones we've seen in a long, long time. 

All in all, the movie is much more than a "liberal circlejerk" as thats the level of thought most of critical drinkers' audience is exhibiting here in the comments, which for any movie fan is a sad thing to witness as, u and i both know, its mostly because of the political environment we are living in, and apparently that lens is a thick, THICK one for many. It saddens me how much effort is being put on creating a polarised, lazy minded society and see it working. It may sound harsh, but an honest look will tell you the same.

